Quick Insights

Key findings from the analysis - prioritized by impact

Technical Debt Hotspot

Found 47 critical and 74 high-priority debt items. These are areas where the team has explicitly noted problems. Consider scheduling time to address the most impactful items.

Executive Summary

Codebase Health: Grade B, Score 85.4/100

LiteLLM scores an overall B grade (85.4/100) across 3,844 files analyzed. The average file-level grade is A-minus, and 97.8% of files score C or above. However, a small cluster of 6 core infrastructure files -- proxy_server.py, utils.py, main.py, router.py, llm_http_handler.py, and prompt_templates/factory.py -- all grade F and carry compounding debt across complexity, duplication, coupling, and churn dimensions simultaneously. These files are the most frequently modified in the repository (131, 395, 268, 200, 35, and 30 commits respectively over the past year), meaning every change to them carries elevated regression risk.

Trajectory: Modestly Improving but Volatile

The overall score trend is upward (slope +0.31 over 12 months, from 61 to 67), but with low confidence (R-squared 0.30) due to erratic swings in the complexity component, which oscillates between 0 and 66. The most recent data point (Jan 30, 2026) shows a 6-point regression from 73 to 67, driven by complexity declining from 44 to 21 during the Claude Agent SDK integration and passthrough OpenAI route work. Coupling is the only component in genuine structural decline (slope -0.22), while duplication (91-93), smells (94-96), TDG (91 flat), SATD (90-91), and cohesion (75-78) have all remained stable.

Top Risks

1. Security vulnerabilities in production code. The SSO OAuth state parameter in ui_sso.py uses a static value instead of a cryptographic nonce, enabling CSRF attacks. The vector DB prompt injection check in prompt_injection_detection.py is a no-op stub that silently passes when enabled. Organization budget enforcement has a confirmed bypass where exceeded budgets do not raise errors.

2. Bus factor of 2. Two contributors (Ishaan Jaff and Krish/Krrish Dholakia) own approximately 63% of all files. 1,769 files (47%) are single-owner silos. The entire enterprise callbacks subsystem (104 files), the policy engine (9 files), and multiple security-critical modules have zero knowledge redundancy.

3. God-class concentration. The top 4 files (proxy_server.py at 11,576 lines, utils.py at 9,141 lines, llm_http_handler.py at 9,193 lines, router.py at 8,816 lines) together represent 38,726 lines of monolithic, high-churn code. ChatUI.tsx in the dashboard has cyclomatic complexity of 326, the highest in the codebase.

Path Forward

The codebase is fundamentally healthy at the file level (A-minus average TDG). The path forward is to address the concentrated debt in the ~84 D/F-graded files, fix the 3 identified security issues, and systematically reduce ownership concentration through cross-training and mandatory review policies for single-owner modules.

Recommendations

Prioritized actions to improve code health

Critical - Address Soon
Fix SSO CSRF vulnerability

Replace the static OAuth state parameter in litellm/proxy/management_endpoints/ui_sso.py (line 1630) with a cryptographically random nonce. Store it in the user session and verify it on callback. This is a known, exploitable vulnerability.

Implement or fail-loud the prompt injection vector DB check

The vector_db_check path in litellm/proxy/hooks/prompt_injection_detection.py (line 184) silently passes. Either implement the similarity check or raise NotImplementedError so users are not misled into thinking they have protection they do not.

Fix organization budget enforcement bypass

The auth path allows organizations to exceed their budget without being blocked. The bug is documented in tests/test_litellm/proxy/auth/test_organization_budget_enforcement.py (line 84). Ensure BudgetExceededError is raised when organization budgets are exceeded.

Implement MCP server deletion cleanup

MCP server deletion in litellm/proxy/management_endpoints/mcp_management_endpoints.py (lines 917-923) skips audit logging, virtual key cleanup, and team cleanup. This leaves orphaned references in the database.

Cross-train maintainers on single-owner critical subsystems

The enterprise callbacks (104 files), policy engine (9 files), auth subsystem, spend tracking (spend_update_queue.py), and MCP chat completions handler (chat_completions_handler.py, sole owner Yuta Saito) all have bus factor 1. Establish mandatory second-reviewer policies and schedule knowledge transfer sessions for these modules.

Begin decomposing proxy_server.py

At 11,576 lines and 131 commits, litellm/proxy/proxy_server.py is the highest-risk file in the repository (hotspot score 0.999). Extract endpoint groups into domain-specific FastAPI routers under proxy/routers/ (completions, embeddings, health, config, admin). This also reduces merge conflict frequency for the 49 contributors who touch this file.

Important - Plan For
Decompose utils.py into focused modules

litellm/utils.py (9,141 lines, 395 commits, 91 authors) is a catch-all utility touched by everyone. Partition into token_counting.py, cost_utils.py, model_utils.py, and response_utils.py. The existing _lazy_imports_registry.py split was a step in the right direction.

Replace secrets plugins boilerplate with a data-driven registry

92 files under enterprise/litellm_enterprise/enterprise_callbacks/secrets_plugins/ follow an identical pattern. Replace with a single RegexSecretDetector class parameterized by service name and regex list. Estimated reduction: ~2,000 lines.

Break UI dashboard dependency cycles and reduce networking.ts coupling

All 5 critical cyclic dependencies and 17 hub smells are in the dashboard UI. networking.ts has 295 dependents and a self-import cycle. Split it into domain-specific API modules (teamsApi.ts, keysApi.ts, modelsApi.ts). Break the 4 pairwise cycles by extracting shared types into third modules.

Split ChatUI.tsx (cyclomatic complexity 326)

ui/litellm-dashboard/src/components/playground/chat_ui/ChatUI.tsx has the highest cyclomatic complexity in the entire codebase at 326. Decompose into smaller components: message list, input area, model selector, streaming handler, and settings panel.

Stabilize proxy/_types.py by splitting into domain-specific type modules

litellm/proxy/_types.py has 87 commits (third highest in the repo) and 3,998 lines. It temporally couples with team_endpoints.py (9 cochanges), key_management_endpoints.py (8 cochanges), and mcp_management_endpoints.py (5 cochanges). Split into team_types.py, key_types.py, mcp_types.py to isolate change impact.

Eliminate duplicated image generation cost calculators and A2A module

6 image cost calculator files are byte-for-byte identical except for one provider enum value -- extract a shared function. The A2A protocol has two identical 476-line transformation modules -- delete one and import from the canonical path.

Extract Responses API shared abstraction

6 files across litellm/llms/, litellm/proxy/, and litellm/responses/ always change together (temporal coupling 0.30-1.00). Extract a shared Responses API interface so changes to response transformation do not require coordinated edits across proxy endpoints and routing.

Maintenance - Keep Doing
Monitor complexity component volatility

The complexity score swings between 0 and 66, driving most overall score volatility. Investigate whether this reflects genuine code quality changes or measurement instability. The underlying average cyclomatic complexity of 3.5 is healthy, but outlier classes (Router CBO=1926, ProxyConfig CBO=905, BaseLLMHTTPHandler CBO=887) need attention.

Reduce coupling trend decline

Coupling is the weakest component (48/100) and has been declining since March 2025 (slope -0.22). Each new feature adds dependency pathways without corresponding decoupling. Establish a review gate that flags PRs increasing coupling in already-high-coupling modules.

Track SATD backlog

346 self-admitted technical debt items exist, with 121 classified as high priority. The SATD score has drifted slightly downward (from 92 to 91 over 8 months), indicating debt accumulates marginally faster than it is resolved. Consider a quarterly debt reduction sprint targeting the 121 high-priority items.

Resolve Krish/Krrish alias for accurate ownership data

Krish Dholakia and Krrish Dholakia appear as separate contributors but are likely the same person. Merging the alias in git mailmap would give accurate ownership percentages and improve bus factor analysis.

Consolidate test fixtures and conftest duplication

15 identical conftest.py files (2,730 lines), 4 copies of large_text.py (1,344 lines), and 3 copies of create_mock_standard_logging_payload.py (3,768 lines) across test directories. Consolidate into shared fixtures at the tests/ root.

Migrate OpenTelemetry logs to public API

litellm/integrations/opentelemetry.py (line 1003) directly constructs SDK-internal LogRecord objects. This already broke in OTEL SDK >= 1.39.0 and will break again on future releases. Migrate to the public OTEL Logs API.

Key Findings

Security -- SSO CSRF vulnerability: litellm/proxy/management_endpoints/ui_sso.py (line 1630) uses a static OAuth state parameter instead of a cryptographic nonce, enabling cross-site request forgery attacks against the SSO login flow.

Security -- No-op prompt injection detection: litellm/proxy/hooks/prompt_injection_detection.py (line 184) declares a vector DB similarity check but the implementation body is pass. Users enabling vector_db_check=True get silent no-op protection.

Security -- Organization budget bypass: Confirmed open bug where organization budget enforcement does not raise BudgetExceededError when budgets are exceeded, documented in tests/test_litellm/proxy/auth/test_organization_budget_enforcement.py (line 84).

Ownership -- Bus factor 2 for the entire project: Ishaan Jaff owns 1,569 files and Krish/Krrish Dholakia owns 808 files. Together they control 63% of the codebase. The enterprise callbacks subsystem (104 files, 96% owned by one person) and the policy engine (9 files, sole owner) are complete knowledge silos.

Hotspots -- 195 critical hotspots, 6 F-graded core files: proxy_server.py (11,576 lines, 131 commits, score 0.999), utils.py (9,141 lines, 395 commits over the year, score 0.999), main.py (7,295 lines, avg complexity 13.5), router.py (8,816 lines), llm_http_handler.py (9,193 lines), and prompt_templates/factory.py are all grade F, combining high size, high churn, and high complexity.

Coupling -- Weakest component at 48/100 and declining: 6 dependency cycles in the UI dashboard, networking.ts has 295 dependents, and Python-side god classes Router (CBO=1926) and ProxyConfig (CBO=905) dominate. Coupling score has declined from 72 to 48 since March 2025.

Duplication -- 3,422 clones, 4.2% rate, with 92 identical secret plugin files: The enterprise secrets plugins directory contains 92 files following the exact same boilerplate pattern. Six image generation cost calculators are byte-for-byte identical except for one enum value. The A2A protocol has a fully duplicated 476-line transformation module.

Temporal coupling -- Responses API 6-file cluster: Six files across 4 packages (llms/, proxy/, responses/) always change together at 0.30-1.00 coupling strength, indicating a missing shared abstraction. The litellm-proxy-extras package mirrors the main Prisma schema at 0.80+ strength, requiring synchronized updates on every schema change.

Hotspots

Files with both high complexity and frequent changes - highest risk for bugs

801 hotspots detected (195 critical, 197 high). The risk is concentrated in two architectural layers: the proxy server layer (litellm/proxy/ with 117 hotspots, 13 critical in guardrails alone) and the provider translation layer (litellm/llms/ with 154 hotspots). Four god-class files dominate the top of the list -- proxy_server.py (11,576 lines, 131 commits, score 0.999), utils.py (9,141 lines, 124 commits, score 0.999), main.py (7,295 lines, 80 commits, score 0.995), and router.py (8,816 lines, 43 commits, score 0.993). These are large, highly complex files that change constantly, meaning every modification carries compounding merge-conflict and regression risk. A secondary cluster exists in the UI dashboard (64 hotspots) where React components like ChatUI.tsx reach cyclomatic complexity of 326, indicating monolithic render logic. The MCP server subsystem (proxy/_experimental/mcp_server/) is a newer area already appearing in critical hotspots with high churn, suggesting it is being developed without sufficient decomposition.

Low Cohesion Classes

Classes doing too many unrelated things - candidates for splitting

Cohesion has been remarkably stable, fluctuating only between 75 and 78 across the entire period, currently at 76. The trend is essentially flat (slope -0.02). Average LCOM across 3,521 classes is 2.3, which is acceptable. Architectural Smells

Structural problems that make the codebase harder to change safely

The codebase has 23 architectural smells across 3,844 components: 5 critical cyclic dependencies, 17 hub modules, and 1 unstable dependency. All cyclic dependencies and nearly all hub smells are concentrated in the dashboard UI (ui/litellm-dashboard), not the core Python library. The core Python backend is structurally clean.

Cyclic Dependencies (5, all Critical severity, all in the dashboard UI):

  • networking.ts has a self-cycle (cycle length 1), importing itself. This file also has 295 dependents (the highest fan-in in the entire codebase), making it the single most coupled module. Any breakage here cascades across virtually the entire dashboard.
  • edit_budget_modal.tsx <-> budget_panel.tsx form a mutual import cycle. These budget components cannot be tested or refactored independently.
  • team_member_view.tsx <-> team_info.tsx form a mutual import cycle. team_info.tsx is also a hub with fan-out of 25, compounding the problem.
  • add_pass_through.tsx <-> pass_through_settings.tsx form a mutual import cycle.
  • ComparisonPanel.tsx <-> CompareUI.tsx form a mutual import cycle in the playground comparison feature. All four pairwise cycles follow the same anti-pattern: a parent component and a child/sibling component import each other directly. The fix in each case is to extract shared state or callbacks into a separate module (a context provider, a shared types file, or a hook) that both components import without importing each other.

Hub Modules (17, all High severity): The most severe hubs by fan-in are:

  • networking.ts (fan_in=295, fan_out=1): The API client layer for the entire dashboard. 295 modules depend on it. This is a classic god module for network calls. Splitting it into domain-specific API modules (e.g., teamsApi.ts, keysApi.ts, modelsApi.ts) would reduce coupling.
  • litellm/integrations/deepeval/types.py (fan_in=166, fan_out=0): The only core Python hub. 166 modules import types from this file. Because it has zero fan-out and defines only types, it is stable (instability=0.0) and low-risk despite the high fan-in. No immediate action needed, but if this file grows further, splitting types by domain would reduce recompilation scope.
  • notifications_manager.tsx (fan_in=135): Used by 135 components for toast/notification display. High fan-in but stable and single-purpose -- acceptable as a shared utility.
  • useAuthorized.ts (fan_in=80): Authorization hook used by 80 components. Stable and appropriate as a cross-cutting concern.
  • key_list.tsx (fan_in=54), dataUtils.ts (fan_in=45), provider_info_helpers.tsx (fan_in=33): Shared helpers with high fan-in but low fan-out; stable and low-risk. The most severe hubs by fan-out are:
  • ChatUI.tsx (fan_out=41, fan_in=3): Imports 41 modules. This is a god component that likely handles rendering, state, API calls, and sub-component orchestration all in one file. Splitting into smaller composable components and extracting business logic into hooks would reduce fragility.
  • team_info.tsx (fan_out=25, fan_in=7): Also involved in a cyclic dependency. High fan-out combined with a cycle makes this the most structurally problematic module in the dashboard.
  • create_key_button.tsx (fan_out=25), ModelsAndEndpointsView.tsx (fan_out=23), UsagePageView.tsx (fan_out=22): Complex view components pulling in many dependencies. These are candidates for decomposition.

Unstable Dependency (1, Medium severity):

  • MCPServerSelector.tsx depends on useMCPAccessGroups.ts with an instability gap of 0.55. The hook is more unstable than its consumer, meaning changes in the hook's transitive dependencies can propagate upward. This is a minor concern given it involves only two components.

Key Observations:

  1. The core Python library (litellm/) is architecturally sound. No cycles, no central connectors, and only one hub (deepeval/types.py) which is a stable types-only module.
  2. All structural risk is in the dashboard UI. The five cycles and the networking.ts super-hub are the top priorities.
  3. The highest-priority fix is networking.ts: it has a self-cycle AND 295 dependents. Resolving the self-import and splitting it into domain-specific API modules would address both the cycle and the hub smell simultaneously.
  4. The four pairwise UI cycles should each be broken by extracting shared types or state into a third module that both sides import.

Dependency Structure

Import graph analysis - cycles, bottlenecks, and instability

The dependency graph contains 3,844 nodes and 2,088 edges with a low average degree of 1.09, meaning most files are loosely connected. 3,033 nodes (79%) are completely isolated with no detected import edges, which is partly an artifact of Python's intra-package imports being harder to resolve statically, but also indicates a genuinely sparse graph overall. The connected structure is dominated by the frontend dashboard (ui/litellm-dashboard), which accounts for virtually all high-centrality nodes and all 6 detected import cycles. The Python backend, despite comprising 2,976 of the 3,844 nodes, shows almost no cross-file dependency edges in this analysis, suggesting the static extraction primarily captured TypeScript/TSX imports.

The most central file by a wide margin is ui/litellm-dashboard/src/components/networking.tsx (PageRank 0.0043, in-degree 181, betweenness 0.0002). With 181 dependents, this file is the single largest point of coupling in the entire codebase. Its instability is appropriately low (0.037, meaning it mostly receives dependencies rather than creating them), which is the correct posture for a foundational module. However, any breaking change to this file will cascade across the dashboard. It also participates in a 3-node import cycle with check_openapi_schema.tsx and key_list.tsx, which should be broken.

Other high-fan-in foundation files are notifications_manager.tsx (135 dependents, instability 0.007), networking.ts under the app directory (101 dependents, instability 0.0), useAuthorized.ts (80 dependents, instability 0.059), and key_list.tsx (53 dependents, instability 0.036). These are all appropriately stable (low instability), meaning they have few outgoing dependencies relative to their incoming ones.

The top betweenness bottlenecks after networking.tsx are key_info_view.tsx (in=5, out=17), useAuthorized.ts (in=80, out=5), and create_key_button.tsx (in=6, out=25). key_info_view.tsx and create_key_button.tsx sit on many shortest paths between modules despite having moderate fan-in, meaning they are communication bridges. Changes to these files risk disrupting information flow across otherwise separate parts of the dashboard.

The highest fan-out files are ChatUI.tsx (41 outgoing dependencies), page.tsx (37 outgoing, 0 incoming, instability 1.0), create_key_button.tsx (25 outgoing), view_logs/index.tsx (25 outgoing), and OldTeams.tsx (25 outgoing). These files are fragile because changes to any of their many dependencies can force them to change. page.tsx at instability 1.0 is a pure consumer, which is acceptable for a top-level entry point. create_key_button.tsx at instability 0.806 with 6 dependents is more concerning because other files depend on it despite its high fragility.

All 6 import cycles are confined to the frontend dashboard and are short (5 of length 2, 1 of length 3). The most impactful cycle is networking.tsx -> key_list.tsx -> check_openapi_schema.tsx -> networking.tsx because networking.tsx is the most central file in the graph. This cycle means networking.tsx cannot be tested or loaded independently of key_list.tsx. The fix is to extract the shared contract (likely a type or validation function) into a separate module that both can import without circular reference. The remaining 5 cycles (budgets, team, pass-through, playground compare, view-logs) are 2-node mutual imports that are typically resolved by extracting shared types or callback interfaces into a third file.

On the Python side, litellm/integrations/deepeval/types.py (in-degree 13) and litellm/types/llms/openai.py (in-degree 11) are the most depended-on Python files detected, both with zero outgoing dependencies (instability 0.0), which is ideal for type definition modules. The lack of deeper Python dependency structure in this graph means the analysis cannot draw conclusions about Python-side architectural health from this data alone.

Key recommendations: (1) Break the networking.tsx cycle by extracting shared types or validation logic into a standalone module. (2) Treat networking.tsx, notifications_manager.tsx, and useAuthorized.ts as stable foundations -- changes to these files should require careful review given their high fan-in. (3) Reduce fan-out in ChatUI.tsx (41 dependencies) by grouping related imports behind facade modules. (4) Address create_key_button.tsx which has both high fan-out (25) and non-trivial fan-in (6) at instability 0.806 -- either reduce its outgoing dependencies or move dependents to import from something more stable. (5) The 5 remaining 2-node cycles are low-severity but should be cleaned up by extracting shared types into dedicated files.

Known Issues

Problems the team has documented but not yet fixed (TODO, FIXME, HACK)

346 SATD items across 7 categories (density 0.49/KLOC). The majority are false positives: the SATD scanner flags the word 'DISABLED' in test descriptions and 'SECURITY' in docstrings/URLs as markers, inflating the test (138) and security (47) categories. After filtering noise, the actionable debt breaks into three priority tiers. TIER 1 -- Security-adjacent debt: SSO state parameter uses a static value instead of a cryptographic nonce (ui_sso.py:1630), prompt injection vector DB check is declared but never implemented (prompt_injection_detection.py:184), organization budget enforcement has a known bypass where exceeded budgets pass instead of raising BudgetExceededError (test_organization_budget_enforcement.py:84), and MCP server deletion skips cleanup of virtual keys and teams (mcp_management_endpoints.py:921-923). TIER 2 -- Design debt with operational risk: two identical HACK comments in Anthropic and Vertex passthrough logging handlers import proxy_logging_obj at call time to sidestep a circular dependency, creating tight coupling (anthropic_passthrough_logging_handler.py:513, vertex_passthrough_logging_handler.py:735); the OTEL logs integration uses deprecated SDK internals that will break on OTEL >= 1.39.0 (opentelemetry.py:1003); health readiness endpoint pings Redis semantic cache on every check, adding unnecessary latency (health_endpoints.py:1202); and the passthrough module has two TODO-REFACTOR comments for request transformation that indicate incomplete migration (passthrough/main.py:251,285). TIER 3 -- Low-priority requirement TODOs: tests hardcode ai.moda IAM roles instead of LiteLLM-owned credentials (3 occurrences in test_secret_manager.py, 3 in test_bedrock_completion.py), multiple Databricks test TODOs for output schema validation (6 occurrences), and scattered UI TODOs for CSV export and tool parsing. The defect category (74 items) is almost entirely test files describing bug scenarios they verify, not actual live bugs. The genuine production defects with inline BUG markers have corresponding fixes already in place (prisma_client.py:327, spend_tracking_utils.py:291). The one confirmed open bug is the organization budget enforcement bypass.

Duplicated Code

Code that appears in multiple places - bugs fixed in one spot may need fixing elsewhere

The codebase contains 3,422 clone pairs across 441 clone groups, totaling roughly 144,000 duplicated lines. About 68% of the duplication is in production code, with the remainder in tests.

Highest-Impact Production Duplication

1. Secrets Plugin Boilerplate (Groups 263, 223, 409) -- ~56,000 lines across 92 files

The single largest source of duplication in the entire codebase. Every file under enterprise/litellm_enterprise/enterprise_callbacks/secrets_plugins/ follows an identical pattern: import re and RegexBasedDetector, define a class with a secret_type property and a denylist property returning compiled regexes. The only variation is the class name, docstring, and regex patterns. This is a textbook case of missing data-driven design. A single RegexSecretDetector class that takes the service name and regex list as constructor arguments -- or a declarative registry (dict/YAML mapping service names to patterns) -- would eliminate roughly 90 files and thousands of lines. Each file is under 30 lines, so the per-file cost is small, but the aggregate maintenance burden is large: adding a new secret detector requires copying an entire file and changing three strings.

Extraction: Replace all secrets_plugins files with a registry in enterprise/litellm_enterprise/enterprise_callbacks/secrets_plugins/registry.py mapping service names to regex patterns. Estimated reduction: ~2,000 lines.

2. Image Generation Cost Calculators (Group 239) -- 6 identical files, ~600 lines

Files litellm/llms/aiml/image_generation/cost_calculator.py, litellm/llms/azure_ai/image_generation/cost_calculator.py, litellm/llms/cometapi/image_generation/cost_calculator.py, litellm/llms/fal_ai/cost_calculator.py, litellm/llms/recraft/cost_calculator.py, and litellm/llms/runwayml/cost_calculator.py are exact copies (type1, similarity 1.0). The only difference is the custom_llm_provider enum value passed to litellm.get_model_info(). This is a trivial extraction.

Extraction: Create litellm/llms/base_llm/image_generation/cost_calculator.py with a single image_generation_cost_calculator(model, image_response, provider) function. Each provider module can either re-export or call it with its provider enum. Estimated reduction: ~125 lines (5 files eliminated).

3. Exception Class Boilerplate (Group 63) -- ~600 lines within litellm/exceptions.py

Four exception classes (RateLimitError, ServiceUnavailableError, BadGatewayError, InternalServerError) have nearly identical __init__, __str__, and __repr__ methods. They differ only in status_code, the message prefix string, and minor attributes. This is a real bug risk -- the hardcoded URL https://cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/ appears in the fake request object across all of them, which looks like a copy-paste artifact.

Extraction: Create a shared _init_error(self, status_code, message_prefix, ...) helper or a mixin class. Estimated reduction: ~150 lines.

4. Provider Error Classes (Group 53) -- ~1,100 lines across 10 provider files

Each provider under litellm/llms/ defines its own error class (e.g., AnthropicTextError, OpenAILikeError, CloudflareError) with the same pattern: store status_code and message, create a fake httpx.Request with a hardcoded URL, create an httpx.Response, call super().__init__(). The only variation is the URL string and the base class. These are spread across litellm/llms/anthropic/, litellm/llms/bedrock/, litellm/llms/cloudflare/, litellm/llms/openai_like/, litellm/llms/vertex_ai/, litellm/llms/vllm/, and deprecated providers.

Extraction: A single ProviderError class in litellm/llms/base_llm/errors.py parameterized by provider URL would replace all of these. Estimated reduction: ~100 lines.

5. A2A Protocol Duplicate Module (Group 238) -- 476 lines, exact copy

litellm/a2a_protocol/litellm_completion_bridge/transformation.py and litellm/a2a_protocol/providers/litellm_completion/transformation.py are byte-for-byte identical (type1, similarity 1.0). One of these is dead code or should be importing from the other.

Extraction: Delete one file and have the other location import from the canonical path. Estimated reduction: ~238 lines.

6. OpenAI Image Generation Transformations (Group 227) -- ~420 lines across 3 files

litellm/llms/openai/image_generation/dall_e_2_transformation.py, dall_e_3_transformation.py, and gpt_transformation.py share the same map_openai_params, transform_response_json_to_openai_response, and response processing logic. They differ primarily in get_supported_openai_params() return values.

Extraction: Move shared methods to a base class (they already inherit from BaseImageGenerationConfig). Override only get_supported_openai_params(). Estimated reduction: ~200 lines.

7. Type Definition Boilerplate (Group 381) -- ~1,200 lines across litellm/types/

Pydantic models in litellm/types/containers/main.py, litellm/types/llms/openai.py, and litellm/types/videos/main.py repeat identical __contains__, get, __getitem__, and json method overrides on every model class. These dictionary-style access methods are duplicated across at least 9 model classes.

Extraction: Create a DictAccessMixin or LiteLLMBaseModel(BaseModel) base class with these methods. Estimated reduction: ~100 lines per file affected.

8. Chat Transformation Stubs (Group 41) -- ~280 lines across 4 providers

litellm/llms/aiml/chat/transformation.py, litellm/llms/hyperbolic/chat/transformation.py, litellm/llms/lambda_ai/chat/transformation.py, and litellm/llms/v0/chat/transformation.py duplicate the same get_supported_openai_params and configuration boilerplate. These providers behave identically to OpenAI-compatible endpoints.

9. Proxy Management Endpoints (Group 138) -- 170 lines

litellm/proxy/management_endpoints/key_management_endpoints.py lines 685-769 and litellm/proxy/management_endpoints/team_endpoints.py lines 286-370 share identical validation/processing logic. This suggests a missing shared utility for management endpoint request handling.

Test Code Duplication (Lower Priority but Notable)

  • conftest.py clones (Group 333): 15 identical conftest.py files across test directories (2,730 lines). These should use a single shared conftest at the tests/ root or import from a shared fixtures module.
  • large_text.py (Group 113): 4 identical copies of test fixture data (1,344 lines). Should be a single shared fixture.
  • create_mock_standard_logging_payload.py (Group 291): 3 identical copies across test directories (3,768 lines). Should be a single shared test utility.
  • UI hook tests (Group 204): 7 test files for React hooks share ~9,000 lines of near-identical test scaffolding.
  • networking.tsx (Groups 278, 394, 194): The dashboard networking module has extensive internal duplication (~10,000 lines across groups) -- repeated API call patterns that should be abstracted into a generic fetcher.

Technical Debt Gradient

Per-file debt scores - prioritize cleanup where it matters most

The codebase scores an average grade of A- across 3,844 files, with 2,602 files (67.7%) at A-minus or above. This is a healthy distribution overall. However, 84 files (2.2%) fall into the D or F range, and 16 files grade F -- these represent concentrated, compounding debt that warrants attention.

Grade distribution: A+ 91, A 1814, A- 697, B+ 425, B 323, B- 146, C+ 104, C 111, C- 49, D 68, F 16.

The primary drivers of poor scores in D/F files are hotspot score and structural complexity. Hotspot score shows the largest gap between D/F files (avg 1.2/10) and the codebase average (8.7/10), meaning the worst files are also the most frequently modified. Structural complexity is the second-largest gap (13.1/20 in D/F vs 19.2/20 overall), followed by coupling (9.0/15 vs 14.8/15) and duplication (8.7/15 vs 13.0/15). Temporal coupling and semantic complexity contribute less to the gap.

Only one file has critical defects: /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/tests/test_litellm/llms/azure/test_azure_common_utils.py (grade F, total 0.0, 1 critical defect). This file should be inspected immediately.

The six F-graded source files represent the core debt hotspots:

  1. /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/litellm/llms/custom_httpx/llm_http_handler.py (score 50.6) -- the worst non-test file. Scores poorly on 4 dimensions simultaneously: duplication (3.1/15), coupling (5.2/15), hotspot (0.1/10), and temporal coupling (4.7/10). This file is highly duplicated, tightly coupled, frequently changed, and changes alongside many other files. Action: extract shared HTTP handling logic into smaller, focused modules; reduce coupling by introducing interfaces for provider-specific behavior.

  2. /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/litellm/litellm_core_utils/prompt_templates/factory.py (score 55.0) -- poor semantic complexity (5.0/15), coupling (7.2/15), and hotspot (0.1/10). This is a large template factory with too many responsibilities. Action: split prompt template construction by provider or message type into separate modules.

  3. /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/litellm/main.py (score 55.1) -- poor duplication (6.1/15), coupling (5.0/15), and hotspot (0.0/10). As the main entry point, it touches everything and is changed constantly. Action: reduce duplication by extracting repeated completion/embedding/etc. setup patterns into shared helpers; decouple by routing through the provider abstractions more cleanly.

  4. /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/litellm/utils.py (score 58.1) -- low duplication (10.4/15) and poor hotspot (0.0/10) combined with near-max structural complexity penalty (12.5/20). Action: break this utility file into focused modules (cost utils, token counting, config helpers, etc.).

  5. /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/litellm/proxy/proxy_server.py (score 59.8) -- duplication (9.9/15), coupling (5.0/15), hotspot (0.0/10). The proxy server file is a monolith. Action: continue extracting endpoint groups into dedicated endpoint modules (which has already been started with management_endpoints/).

  6. /Users/albanda/dev/tmp/litellm/litellm/router.py (score 60.0) -- duplication (10.2/15), coupling (5.0/15), hotspot (0.1/10). Action: extract routing strategies and retry/fallback logic into separate modules under router_utils/.

Among the 35 D-graded source files, a pattern emerges: the proxy layer is disproportionately represented (16 of 84 D/F files are under litellm/proxy/). Key proxy files to address: key_management_endpoints.py (62.2), litellm_logging.py (62.4), ui_sso.py (62.8), spend_management_endpoints.py (63.8), proxy/utils.py (64.0), and team_endpoints.py (64.2). These all share the same profile: maxed-out structural complexity penalty (12.5/20), low coupling scores, and near-zero hotspot scores -- they are large, complex files that change very frequently.

Debt is concentrated rather than spread. The top 84 files (2.2% of the codebase) account for all D/F grades, and they cluster in: litellm/proxy/ (16 files), tests/test_litellm/ (21 files), and litellm core modules (main.py, utils.py, router.py, init.py). The remaining 97.8% of files grade C or above.

The 43 D/F-graded test files are also worth noting. Large, duplicated test files like test_completion.py, test_key_generate_prisma.py, and test_bedrock_completion.py score poorly due to copy-paste test patterns. Extracting shared fixtures and parameterizing tests would improve these scores.

In summary: the codebase is in good shape overall (A- average), but a small cluster of core infrastructure files -- the main entry point, the proxy server, the router, and the HTTP handler -- carry compounding debt across multiple dimensions. These files are simultaneously complex, duplicated, tightly coupled, and among the most frequently changed in the project. Addressing them would have outsized impact on long-term maintainability.

Historical Trends

How code quality has changed over time

The LiteLLM codebase shows a modest upward trajectory over the past year (slope +0.31, R-squared 0.30), rising from 61 to 67. However, the low R-squared indicates high volatility rather than steady improvement. The overall score is dominated by the complexity component, which oscillates erratically between 0 and 66, driving nearly all major inflection points. When complexity scores above zero, the overall score jumps into the high 60s-70s range; when it collapses back to 0, scores drop to 61-62. The other six components are remarkably stable: duplication (91-93), smells (94-96), tdg (91 flat), satd (89-92), and cohesion (75-78) have barely moved in a year. Coupling is the one component showing genuine decline (slope -0.22), drifting from 43 down to 48 area with occasional spikes. The codebase is fundamentally stable on most health dimensions but has an unresolved complexity measurement instability that makes the trend line appear more volatile than the underlying code quality warrants. The latest data point (Jan 30, 2026) at 67 represents a 6-point drop from Jan 20 driven entirely by complexity falling from 44 to 21, coinciding with the v1.81.x release cycle and Claude Agent SDK integration work.

Change Activity

How frequently code is being modified

Churn analysis over 365 days across 11,136 changed files (1.54M additions, 532K deletions, mean 4 commits/file). Churn is moderately distributed: the top 10 source files account for only 7% of total source churn, and the top 50 for 19.4%, meaning instability is spread across many files rather than concentrated in a few. However, 19 source files show sustained churn (active >300 days with >100 commits each), and these are the primary risk areas.

Highest-churn source files by score: litellm/proxy/proxy_server.py (381 commits, 11.6K LOC, 47 authors, relative churn 1.19x), litellm/utils.py (395 commits, 9.1K LOC, 91 authors, relative churn 1.06x), litellm/init.py (334 commits, 1.7K LOC, 72 authors, relative churn 3.45x), litellm/proxy/_types.py (315 commits, 4K LOC, 37 authors), litellm/main.py (268 commits, 7.3K LOC, 64 authors), litellm/litellm_core_utils/litellm_logging.py (218 commits, 5.4K LOC, 38 authors), and litellm/router.py (200 commits, 8.8K LOC, 32 authors).

Commit pattern analysis reveals that the top files churn for different reasons. proxy_server.py is a feature magnet receiving new endpoints (guardrail policies, MCP, model search, SSO) mixed with bug fixes (migration issues, root path fixes, mypy fixes), and reverts -- a classic God Object accumulating responsibilities. utils.py has a similar pattern: feature additions (new providers like Vercel AI Gateway, ChatGPT subscriptions), performance optimizations, and bug fixes from 91 different authors, indicating it serves as a catch-all utility that everyone touches. router.py shows a concerning mix of reverts, bug fixes for retry logic and error handling, and feature additions -- the reverts (e.g., reverting loadbalancing billing fix, reverting staging merges) suggest instability in changes landing here. litellm_logging.py receives performance fixes (removing premature model.dump), bug fixes for duplicate logs, and new feature integrations, with at least one revert of a performance optimization.

Files with the highest relative churn among substantial source files: litellm/proxy/proxy_cli.py (7.18x relative churn, 876 LOC, 32 commits), ui/litellm-dashboard/src/components/view_logs/index.tsx (6.42x, 1072 LOC, 64 commits over 361 days), pyproject.toml (6.19x, 201 LOC, 395 commits), ui/litellm-dashboard/src/app/page.tsx (6.03x, 600 LOC, 100 commits), litellm/init.py (3.45x, 1726 LOC), and litellm/proxy/_experimental/mcp_server/mcp_server_manager.py (2.56x, 2507 LOC, 122 commits over 303 days). High relative churn in init.py (3.45x) is particularly notable -- it suggests constant additions of module-level exports and configuration, reinforcing that the package's public interface is unstable.

The MCP server files (mcp_server_manager.py at 2.56x relative churn with 122 commits, and server.py at 2.51x with 104 commits) represent a rapidly evolving feature area that has been actively developed for 10 months. This is likely natural growth churn from an actively developed feature rather than a design problem, but the sustained pace warrants monitoring.

Key structural risks: (1) proxy_server.py at 11.6K LOC with 381 commits is a monolith accumulating diverse responsibilities -- it would benefit from further decomposition. (2) utils.py touched by 91 authors over 366 days is a shared dependency that everyone modifies, creating merge conflict risk and a high defect surface. (3) The presence of reverts in router.py and litellm_logging.py indicates that changes to core routing and logging infrastructure are fragile and not adequately covered by tests before merging. (4) litellm/init.py with 3.45x relative churn for a 1.7K LOC file means its contents have been rewritten 3.4 times over, reflecting an unstable public API surface.

Temporal Coupling

Files that frequently change together - reveals hidden dependencies not in the import graph

The temporal coupling data (1311 pairs, 406 after filtering UI build artifacts) reveals several notable patterns.

  1. RESPONSES API CLUSTER -- STRONGEST CROSS-BOUNDARY SIGNAL

Six files form a tightly coupled cluster that always change together, spanning four distinct packages:

  • litellm/llms/base_llm/responses/transformation.py
  • litellm/llms/openai/responses/transformation.py
  • litellm/proxy/response_api_endpoints/endpoints.py
  • litellm/proxy/route_llm_request.py
  • litellm/proxy/management_endpoints/mcp_management_endpoints.py
  • litellm/responses/main.py

Each of these files has 5 coupling partners within the cluster (coupling strength 0.30-1.00, 3 cochanges each). This is a feature under active development (Responses API / MCP support), and the tight coupling across litellm/llms/, litellm/proxy/, and litellm/responses/ suggests a missing abstraction. The transformation layer, proxy endpoints, routing logic, and response orchestration are all entangled. Action: Extract a shared Responses API interface or configuration struct that makes the contract between these layers explicit, so changes to response transformation do not require coordinated edits across proxy endpoints and routing.

  1. LITELLM-PROXY-EXTRAS AND PRISMA CLIENT -- CROSS-REPO DUPLICATION

litellm-proxy-extras/litellm_proxy_extras/utils.py couples with litellm/proxy/db/prisma_client.py at 0.86 strength (6 cochanges out of 7 commits). The proxy-extras package also mirrors schema.prisma (0.80-0.83 strength, 8-10 cochanges). This indicates that litellm-proxy-extras duplicates or wraps database logic from the main proxy, and every schema change requires a synchronized update in both places. Action: Consolidate the shared Prisma schema and DB utilities into a single source of truth, or make the extras package depend on the main package's schema directly rather than maintaining a parallel copy.

  1. PROXY _TYPES.PY AS AN UNSTABLE INTERFACE

litellm/proxy/_types.py changes alongside team_endpoints.py (9 cochanges), key_management_endpoints.py (8 cochanges), and mcp_management_endpoints.py (5 cochanges). This file acts as a shared type definition that is modified whenever endpoint logic changes, which means the type definitions and the endpoint implementations are not properly decoupled. Action: Stabilize the proxy types by separating request/response models per endpoint domain (team types, key types, MCP types) rather than using a single monolithic _types.py that forces all endpoints to co-evolve.

  1. CORE MODULE HUB: init.py / _lazy_imports_registry.py / utils.py / types/utils.py / constants.py

These five files form a diffuse coupling hub at the root of the litellm package. litellm/init.py and litellm/_lazy_imports_registry.py co-change 10 times (0.45 strength). litellm/utils.py co-changes with init.py, _lazy_imports_registry.py, and types/utils.py 8 times each. This is expected for core infrastructure but the breadth (utils.py also couples with llms/custom_httpx/llm_http_handler.py at 5 cochanges) suggests utils.py is a god module that mediates too many concerns. Action: Continue decomposing litellm/utils.py into focused modules (the _lazy_imports_registry.py split was a step in the right direction).

  1. PROVIDER TYPE COUPLING

Several provider implementations couple tightly with their type definitions in litellm/types/llms/: vertex_ai (5 cochanges, 0.38), bedrock (4 cochanges, 0.44), anthropic (3 cochanges, 0.75). The anthropic coupling is notable -- litellm/llms/anthropic/experimental_pass_through/messages/transformation.py couples with litellm/types/llms/anthropic.py at 0.75 strength, meaning 3 out of 4 changes to the transformation require type changes. This is a sign that the type definitions are too tightly bound to a single transformation implementation rather than representing a stable provider contract.

  1. RECRAFT / VERTEX IMAGE EDIT -- HIDDEN SHARED ABSTRACTION

litellm/llms/recraft/image_edit/transformation.py and litellm/llms/vertex_ai/image_edit/vertex_imagen_transformation.py have 1.00 coupling strength (3 cochanges). These are in completely separate provider packages with no obvious import relationship. This strongly suggests a shared image editing abstraction that is implicit rather than explicit. Action: Extract a common base image edit transformation class or protocol that both providers implement, making the shared contract visible.

  1. GIGACHAT -- EXPECTED NEW-PROVIDER COUPLING

All 8 files in litellm/llms/gigachat/ form a perfect 1.0-strength clique (3 cochanges each). This is expected for a newly added provider where all files were introduced together. It is not a design concern but will become one if the coupling persists as the provider matures.

PRIORITY RANKING:

  • High: Responses API cluster (cross-boundary, active development, 6-file clique)
  • High: litellm-proxy-extras schema duplication (0.80+ strength, maintenance burden)
  • Medium: proxy/_types.py monolith (high cochange count, growing surface area)
  • Medium: Recraft/Vertex image edit hidden abstraction (1.0 strength cross-provider)
  • Low: Core module hub (expected for central infrastructure, ongoing decomposition already in progress)

Glossary of Terms

Health Score

A weighted composite metric (0-100) measuring overall code quality. Above 80 is good, 60-80 needs attention, below 60 is concerning.

Hotspot

A file that is both complex AND frequently changed. These are the highest-risk areas because they're hard to change safely but get changed often.

Bus Factor

The minimum number of people who would need to leave before critical knowledge is lost. Higher is better; 1 is a serious risk.

Knowledge Silo

A file that only one person has ever touched. If that person leaves, the knowledge goes with them.

Cyclomatic Complexity

The number of independent paths through code. More paths means more test cases needed and more ways things can go wrong.

Cognitive Complexity

How hard code is to understand. Accounts for nesting, breaks in flow, and things that make humans struggle to follow the logic.

LCOM (Cohesion)

How well a class's methods work together. High LCOM means methods don't share data - the class is probably doing too many unrelated things.

CBO (Coupling)

How many other classes a class depends on. High coupling means changes ripple through the codebase - everything is connected to everything.

Churn Rate

How frequently a file changes. High churn indicates instability - the code may be unclear, have bugs, or be undergoing active development.

Self-Admitted Technical Debt (SATD)

Code issues the team has documented (TODO, FIXME, HACK, XXX). These represent known shortcuts that need eventual attention.

Code Clone / Duplicate

Similar code appearing in multiple places. When a bug is fixed in one spot, it may need fixing elsewhere. Candidates for refactoring into shared functions.

Technical Debt Gradient

Per-file quality score (0-100) combining complexity, duplication, coupling, and other factors. Lower scores mean more accumulated debt.

Temporal Coupling

Files that frequently change together in the same commits. High temporal coupling suggests hidden dependencies not visible in the import graph.

Architectural Smell

A structural pattern that violates design principles: cyclic dependencies, hub-like modules, or stable code depending on unstable code.

Instability

Ratio of outgoing to total dependencies. 0 = maximally stable (many things depend on it), 1 = maximally unstable (depends on many things).

PageRank

Importance of a file in the dependency graph. Files with high PageRank are depended on by many other important files.
